There are some traditional substances like bread, olive oil, red wine, mineral water, etc. that don't really have any scientific justification for their pleasantness, but it seems inherently tied to the quality craftsmanship of their production or the quality of their source.

E.g. Peat talked about baking sourdough and his intestine not reacting to it like to any other, pungent olive oil from Greece pressed in a garden, good wine a sommelier may trace to a valley in 1980. These are so unlike the common versions of themselves, but no one rly knows why.
The best bread is still starch, maybe a bit less gluten under the microscope, but it is so unlike its constituting parts that one is forced to call onto infinitesimals to hope to explain it
